{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180515110538|841359676","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"John_Yarmuth","to":"John Yarmuth"}],"pages":{"3983746":{"pageid":3983746,"ns":0,"title":"John Yarmuth","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-06-11T23:42:08Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = John Yarmuth\n|image       = John Yarmuth official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Kentucky]]\n|district    = {{ushr|KY|3|3rd}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2007\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Anne Northup]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = John Allan Yarmuth\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|11|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (before 1985)<br>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (1985\u2013present)\n|spouse      = Catherine Yarmuth\n|children    = 1 son\n|education   = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Georgetown University]]\n}}\n'''John Allan Yarmuth''' (born November 4, 1947) is an American politician and former newspaper editor serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Kentucky|3|}} since 2007. His district encompasses the vast majority of the [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville Metro Area]]. Since 2013, he has been the only [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of [[United States congressional delegations from Kentucky|Kentucky's congressional delegation]]. Yarmuth currently serves as the [[ranking member]] of the [[United States House Committee on the Budget]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-resolution/7 | title= House Resolution 7| publisher = United States Congress| first = Joseph | last= Crowley | date = January 7, 2017|access-date = February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nYarmuth was born in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], the son of Edna E. (n\u00e9e Klein) and Stanley R. Yarmuth. He is descended from Jewish immigrants from Russia and Austria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/yarmuth.htm |title=yarmuth |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Atherton High School]].<ref name=bio>[http://yarmuth.house.gov/johns-biography/ Official House Biography] Retrieved July 5, 2012.</ref> He later graduated from [[Yale University]], majoring in American Studies, and attended [[Georgetown University Law Center]].<ref name=bio />\n\nHe worked for Republican [[U.S. Senator]] [[Marlow Cook]] from 1971 to 1975, then returned to [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] and launched his publishing career by founding the ''Louisville Today'' magazine, which operated from 1976 to 1982. He later worked as a vice-president of University Relations at the [[University of Louisville]].<ref name=bio />\n\n==Publisher and columnist==\nIn 1990, Yarmuth founded the ''[[Louisville Eccentric Observer]]'' (LEO), a weekly newspaper for which he wrote a generally [[progressivism|progressive]] political column that was usually featured on the first page. In 2003, Yarmuth sold LEO to a company owned by [[Times Publishing Company]] of [[Pennsylvania]], owner of the ''[[Erie Times-News]].'' Yarmuth remained on board as a columnist and consultant until January 2006, when he put his column on hiatus to run for Congress.<ref name=bio />\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nYarmuth took office on January 3, 2007. As of 2017, he is serving his sixth term as Congressman.\n\nAfter his first year in Congress, Yarmuth donated his post-tax congressional salary of just over $120,000 to various charities in Louisville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yarmuthforcongress.com/yarmuth.php/news/yarmuth-donates-2007-congressional-salary-to-louisville-non-profit-organizations |title=Yarmuth For Congress \u00bb Campaign Blog \u00bb Yarmuth Donates 2007 Congressional Salary to Louisville Non-Profit Organizations |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412080919/http://www.yarmuthforcongress.com/yarmuth.php/news/yarmuth-donates-2007-congressional-salary-to-louisville-non-profit-organizations |archivedate=April 12, 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2008, Yarmuth endorsed [[Barack Obama]] in his bid for the Democratic Party nomination for [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Yarmuth endorses Obama |date=February 8, 2008 |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |author=Carroll, James |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080208/NEWS01/80208013/1008/NEWS01}}{{dead link|date=April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 2008, Yarmuth voted against the TARP bailout plan, as negotiated by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]],  Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]], President [[George W. Bush]], House Minority Leader [[John Boehner]], and Senate Minority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Four Congressmen vote No |date=September 29, 2008 |work=[[Lexington Herald Leader]] |author=Abdullah, Halimah |url=http://www.kentucky.com/181/story/540032.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004031451/http://www.kentucky.com/181/story/540032.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=October 4, 2008 |df= }}</ref>  However, he did vote in favor of the second version of the bailout bill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yarmuth Thinks Bailout Bill Stinks, Votes For It Anyway |url=http://www.beloblog.com/WHAS_Blogs/PoliticalBlogger/2008/10/yarmuth-thinks-bailout-bill-st.html |publisher=[[WHAS-TV]] |date=October 3, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202221210/http://www.beloblog.com/WHAS_Blogs/PoliticalBlogger/2008/10/yarmuth-thinks-bailout-bill-st.html |archivedate=December 2, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nYarmuth said he was so \"nauseated\" by a moment of silence for [[Michael Jackson]] on the House floor that he left the chamber. \"I thought it was outrageous,\" he said. \"In my two and a half years, we've not done this for anybody else. We've done it for former members and that's about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Petchenik|first=Mike|title=Yarmuth 'Nauseated' By Jackson Tribute|url=http://www.wlky.com/news/19995422/detail.html|work=WLKY.com|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter defeating Northup for the second time, Yarmuth was rewarded by the [[Democratic Steering and Policy Committee]] with a spot on the influential [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means Committee]]. On the committee, Yarmuth worked on issues on which he campaigned before the 2008 general election: [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], [[pension]], [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], and [[Medicaid]] issues.\n\nAt a September 2009 town hall meeting, constituents were unhappy with Yarmuth's decision to support the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. \"Yarmuth stayed calm in the face of boos and catcalls from some in the audience\" according to an Associated Press report. \"He warned that the current health care system is an unsustainable drain on businesses and the nation's economy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbko.com/news/headlines/56885527.html |title=Yarmuth faces boisterous town hall meeting |publisher=WBKO |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105180025/http://www.wbko.com/news/headlines/56885527.html |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Yarmuth introduced a bill alongside Republican Congressman [[Walter B. Jones, Jr.|Walter Jones]] that would seek to overturn key parts of the controversial court case ''[[Citizens United v. FEC]]''. The legislation would also give Congress the power to enact mandatory public financing for Congressional candidates and create a national holiday for voting purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Phillip M. Bailey |url=http://archives.wfpl.org/2011/12/20/yarmuth-introduces-constitutional-amendment-to-overturn-citizens-united-case/ |title=Yarmuth Introduces Constitutional Amendment to Overturn Citizens United Case |publisher=Archives.wfpl.org |date=December 20, 2011 |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Yarmuth voted against the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] due to a controversial provision which allows the government and the military to indefinitely detain American citizens and others without trial.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/ndaa-bill-how-did-your-congress-member-vote-384362?page=1 |title=NDAA Bill: How Did Your Congress Member Vote? |publisher=Ibtimes.com |date=December 16, 2011 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=House Vote 291 - Passes the {{sic|nolink=y|the}} National Defense Authorization Act|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/112/house/2/291|work=Inside Congress|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|accessdate=September 27, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522011114/http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/112/house/2/291|archivedate=May 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Yarmuth introduced the [[Fair Elections Now Act]], which would establish a public financing system for Congressional campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yarmuth.house.gov/get-money-out-of-politics/ |title=Congressman John Yarmuth : Get Money Out of Politics |website=Yarmuth.house.gov |date=October 14, 2016 |accessdate=November 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://yarmuth.house.gov/press/rep-yarmuth-introduces-public-financing-bill-to-get-money-out-of-politics/ |title=Congressman John Yarmuth : Press : Rep. Yarmuth Introduces Public Financing Bill to Get Money Out of Politics |website=Yarmuth.house.gov |date=January 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Yarmuth once again made an attempt at removing \"dark money\" from the political sphere by Proposing HR 2125, the Keeping our Campaigns Honest Act of 2015, however the bill realistically had no chance of passing in the 114th Congress in which it was proposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr2125|title=Keeping Our Campaigns Honest Act of 2015 (H.R. 2125)|publisher=GovTrack.us|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nYarmuth signed onto a \"Medicare for All\" bill in the House, along with 120 other Democrats in 2018, supporting [[single-payer healthcare]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sullivan|first1=Peter|title=Democrats march toward single-payer health care|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/375376-democrats-march-toward-single-payer-health-care|website=The Hill|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* Ranking Member, [[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yarmuth.house.gov/committees/ |title=Congressman John Yarmuth : Committees |website=Yarmuth.house.gov |date=October 15, 2016 |accessdate=November 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/john_yarmuth/412211|title=John Yarmuth, Representative for Kentucky's 3rd Congressional District|publisher=GovTrack.us|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Party leadership===\n* Regional Whip\n\n===Congressional Caucuses===\nThe following is a list of John Yarmuth's Congressional Caucus memberships:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciclt.net/sn/pol/po_detail.aspx?P_ID=&ClientCode=masc&MemID=21914|title=Elected Official Detail Page|publisher=Municipal Association of South Carolina|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*Co-Chair [[Ohio River Basin Congressional Caucus]]\n*Co-Chair [[Congressional Bourbon Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Musician's Caucus]]\n*[[Fragile X Caucus]]\n*[[Home Health Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Horse Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Youth Challenge Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Caucus on the Mississippi River]]\n*[[Congressional Aluminium Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Business Owner's Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Caucus on Bosnia]]\n*[[Congressional Caucus on Tourette Syndrome]]\n*[[Congressional Energy Savings Performance Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Deaf Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional High Technology Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Azerbaijan Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Adult Literacy Caucus]]\n*[[Populist Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Baby Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Arthritis Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Mobility Air Force Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Recycling Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Steel Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Lupus Caucus]]\n*[[Green Schools Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Career and Technical Education Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Vision Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Zoo and Aquarium Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Boating Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Social Work Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Childhood Cancer Caucus]]\n*[[Public Broadcasting Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Caucus for Competitiveness in Entertainment Technology]]\n*[[Congressional Humanities Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Nursing Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Heart and Stroke Coalition]]\n*[[House National Service Caucus]]\n*[[National Guard and Reserve Components Caucus]]\n*[[Community College Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Historic Preservation Caucus]]\n*[[House Small Brewers Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Multiple Sclerosis Caucus]]\n*[[Coalition for Autism Research and Education]]\n*[[Congressional Cystic Fibrosis Caucus]]\n*[[Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency Caucus]]\n*[[Bicameral Congressional Caucus on Parkinson's Disease]]\n*[[Congressional Caucus on Foster Youth]]\n*[[Congressional Bike Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Animal Protection Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Diabetes Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|author=|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Political campaigns==\n\n===2006===\nYarmuth filed candidacy papers on January 31, 2006, to represent {{ushr|Kentucky|3|}}. Having won the Democratic primary on May 16, defeating [[Andrew Horne]], Burrell Charles Farnsley and James W. Moore, he defeated incumbent [[Anne Northup]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]) in November of that year.\n\nOn August 7, 2006, ''[[The Courier-Journal]]'' reported that ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' revealed a week before that the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] had earmarked $51.5 million for television advertising in 32 congressional districts across the nation, but none for Yarmuth's challenge in the Third Congressional District.<ref>{{cite news |title=National Democratic campaign doesn't plan ads for Yarmuth |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1755353091.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+7,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=A.1&desc=National+Democratic+campaign+doesn't+plan+ads+for+Yarmuth |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=August 7, 2006 |last=Stewart |first=Kay |accessdate=September 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, a ''Courier-Journal'' article stated that a [[WHAS-TV|WHAS11]]/[[SurveyUSA]] poll revealed the race had tightened dramatically, with Yarmuth leading Northup 48 to 47 percent. Another poll a month earlier had Northup leading by 6 points.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poll: Northup, Yarmuth race in dead heat |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1755385121.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+20,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=B.1&desc=Rep.+Northup's+campaign+cash+far+exceeds+that+of+foe+Yarmuth |last=Stewart |first=Kay |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=October 20, 2006 |accessdate=November 9, 2006}}</ref> A WHAS11/SurveyUSA poll released on November 2 showed Yarmuth leading Northup 52 to 44 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.whas11.com/news/politics/local/stories/WHAS11_TOP_SurveyUSAPollYarmuthNorthup.e9a3004.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211160301/http://www.whas11.com/news/politics/local/stories/WHAS11_TOP_SurveyUSAPollYarmuthNorthup.e9a3004.html |archivedate=February 11, 2007 |title=Yarmuth ahead in new poll |date=November 2, 2006 |accessdate=November 9, 2006 |work=whas11.com |first=Mark |last=Hebert}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, Yarmuth told ''Courier-Journal'' reporter Kay Stewart that he would donate his congressional salary\u2014which would be $168,500 in 2007\u2014to local charity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Northup attacks Yarmuth's Wealth -- Hypocrisy? |url=http://northupforcongress.blogspot.com/2006/10/northup-attacks-yarmuths-wealth.html |last=Stewart |first=Kay |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=October 26, 2006 |accessdate=January 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBecause polls close early in Kentucky, many analysts saw this race as a key indicator and it immediately became one of the most watched House races in the nation.\n\nYarmuth defeated Northup in the general election. He garnered 122,139 votes (51%) to Northup's 116,157 votes (48%). Independent candidates garnered 2,896 votes (1%).\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2008#District 3}}\nYarmuth ran unopposed in the primary, and faced Anne Northup in a rematch of the 2006 general election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/blogs/politics/2008/01/roberts-probably-out-northup-considers.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120729031002/http://www.courier-journal.com/blogs/politics/2008/01/roberts-probably-out-northup-considers.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |title=Roberts probably out, Northup considers return |author=Gerth, Joe |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=January 16, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"ap2008\">{{cite news|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/K/KY_NORTHUP_CAMPAIGN_KYOL- |title=Northup to run to regain former congressional seat, adviser says |author=Schreiner, Bruce |work=Associated Press |date=January 28, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Northup Files To Run For Old Congressional Seat |url=http://www.wlky.com/news/15159131/detail.html |work=WLKY.com |publisher=Internet Broadcasting Systems, Inc. |date=January 28, 2008 |accessdate=April 20, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717065350/http://www.wlky.com/news/15159131/detail.html |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nYarmuth won the 2008 election with 59% of the vote.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/individual/#mapHKY/H/03|title=2008 General Election Results|publisher=CNN|date=November 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2010#District 3}}\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Todd Lally and Independent Michael D. Hansen. Yarmuth was re-elected successfully with 53% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fox41.com/story/13430643/kentucky-3rd-district|title=John Yarmuth wins Kentucky 3rd District|date=November 2, 2010|accessdate=November 2, 2010|publisher=[[WDRB]]}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2012#District 3}}\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Brooks Wicker and Independent candidate Robert L. Devore Jr.  Yarmuth received 206,385 votes (63.96%), Brooks Wicker received 111,452 votes (23.32%), and Robert L. Devore Jr. received 4,819 votes (1.49%).\n\n===2014===\nIn the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014|2014 General Election]], Yarmuth was challenged by Republican Dr. Michael McFarlane and Independent Gregory Puccetti.  On October 6, 2014, [[Kentucky Educational Television]] hosted a [[Leaders' debate|debate]] which was broadcast live on Louisville's KET, and was moderated by KET host Bill Goodman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/politics-blog/2014/10/06/yarmuth-and-macfarlane-debate-on-ket/16838337/|title= Yarmuth and MacFarlane debate on KET | publisher= the Courier Journal | date = October 6, 2014 | access-date = February 27, 2018}}</ref>  Yarmuth went on to win reelection with 63.5% of the votes cast.\n\n===2016===\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Harold Bratcher and Independent Everett Corley.  Yarmuth won with 63% of the vote, receiving 212,388 votes.  Harold Bratcher received 37% of the vote, totaling 122,085 ballots cast in his name.  Everett Corley received no votes in the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/elections/live_results/2016_general/house/ky.html |title=Live Results : 2016 KENTUCKY HOUSE ELECTION RESULTS |website=Realclearpolitics.com |accessdate=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn April 17, 2017, Yarmuth announced that he would run for a seventh term in the 2018 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weku.fm/post/congressman-john-yarmuth-run-re-election-2018|title=Congressman John Yarmuth Running for reelection in 2018|website=weku.fm|accessdate= April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nIn 2003, Yarmuth and former [[WHAS-AM]] radio talk show host [[John Ziegler (talk show host)|John Ziegler]] debated political issues on the weekly [[WAVE (TV)|WAVE]] program ''Yarmuth & Ziegler'', with Yarmuth taking the [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] side and Ziegler, the [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] side. On a successor program, ''Hot Button'', which ran from September 2004 to December 2005, he faced off with conservative Jim Milliman.\n\nYarmuth appeared on the March 8, 2007, episode of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' in the show's \"[[Better Know a District]]\" series. In a parody of Yarmuth's former ''Yarmuth & Ziegler'' debate series, host [[Stephen Colbert (character)|Stephen Colbert]] prodded Yarmuth into a point/counterpoint style debate. After agreeing to the \"debate,\" Colbert forced Yarmuth to defend the shredding of [[kitten]]s in [[wood chipper]]s, which Yarmuth gamely proceeded to do. Colbert referred to Yarmuth as a real life [[Bruce Wayne]], and presented him with a framed print of his congressional photo with a [[Batman]] mask photoshopped over his face.<ref>{{cite news |first=James R. |last=Carroll |title=Yarmuth jokes on the 'Colbert Report' |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=March 9, 2007 | accessdate=March 9, 2007 |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070309/NEWS01/70309021}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYarmuth has served on many boards including the Bingham Child Guidance Center and [[Kentucky Country Day School]]. He is Kentucky's first [[Jewish]] congressman.  Yarmuth and his wife, Cathy Yarmuth, have one son, Aaron, who is a graduate of Kentucky Country Day. Aaron is currently the owner of the ''Louisville Eccentric Observer''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://yarmuth.house.gov/ Congressman John Yarmuth] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.yarmuthforcongress.com/ John Yarmuth for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Kentucky/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/John_Yarmuth_%5BD-3%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=y000062 | votesmart=58579 | fec=H6KY03124 | congress=john-yarmuth/1853 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724125736/http://watchdog.net/p/john_yarmuth/contribs Campaign Contributors to Rep. John Yarmuth] at watchdog.net\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anne Northup]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Kentucky|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Kentucky's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Welch]]<br>D-[[Vermont]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=152nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Niki Tsongas]]<br>D-[[Massachusetts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{KY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseChairs}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 110th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Kentucky]]}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/110}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/111}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/112}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/113}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/114}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yarmuth, John}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n[[Category:American magazine publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:American newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Atherton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]"}]}}}}